Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday from snowy Brooklyn!
I have a bunch of goals for this newsletter. Our mission is to make the wor=
ld more optimistic. I want to invest in and tell the stories of companies t=
hat are bending the world=E2=80=99s trajectory upwards. But there=E2=80=99s=
 one immediate short-term thing I really want to get across: the world is g=
oing to keep getting much weirder, really fast.=C2=A0
Instead of dismissing the latest Weird New Thing as a fad or temporary (tra=
nsitory?) insanity, I want you to see that the Weird New Thing is just a sm=
all taste of a Much Weirder Future Thing.=C2=A0I want you to start taking w=
eird shit more seriously.=20
We=E2=80=99re in the middle of one of those =E2=80=9Ceverything is changing=
=E2=80=9D times. And in times like these, it=E2=80=99s helpful to zoom out,=
 look back, and look forward. It=E2=80=99s impossible to predict the future=
 with any meaningful accuracy, but it is possible to take the present much =
more seriously.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The AppetiZIRP
Let=E2=80=99s start with a hot take: ZIRP Phenomena are really just little =
glimpses into the future. AppetiZIRPs, if you will, for the much wilder mai=
n course.=C2=A0
The conversation around the Fed=E2=80=99s Zero Interest Rate Policy, or ZIR=
P, typically runs in one causal direction. The Fed lowered rates to avert c=
risis and kept them low for a decade. That led to all sorts of wacky behavi=
or. With rates going back up, the wacky behavior will go away, the temporar=
y insanity will stop, and we=E2=80=99ll look back and laugh at all of the s=
illy things people did back then.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re already laughing. =E2=80=9CX was a ZIRP phenomenon=E2=80=9D h=
as become a meme on Twitter. My friend Austin asked for, and received, a bu=
nch of examples here:
That may be the correct lens through which to view the past few years. Very=
 smart people seem to think so. But allow me to play Devil=E2=80=99s Advoca=
te and argue the side that Justin Poirier laid out succinctly here:=C2=A0
What if the causality runs in the other direction? In that telling, we live=
 in a world in which fewer and fewer people need to work to meet humanity=
=E2=80=99s basic survival needs. At least, in America, we live in a country=
 in which fewer and fewer Americans need to work to meet Americans=E2=80=99=
 basic survival needs, thanks to a combination of increased productivity an=
d globalization. As a rough proxy, the percentage of Americans who work in =
agriculture and manufacturing has shrunk dramatically over the past couple =
of centuries. Each has halved again in just the past forty years, during wh=
ich rates have been in a steady downtrend. What if the proportion of the po=
pulation needed to meet our basic needs is the prime mover, and rates are a=
 response?=C2=A0
Through this lens, low rates and ZIRP are kind of like indirect, trickle-do=
wn Universal Basic Income (UBI), keeping people employed in jobs that would=
 have looked like luxuries, or even games, to our fairly recent ancestors.=
=C2=A0
In just the past ~30 years, the number of employees needed to generate $1 m=
illion in revenue at S&P 500 companies has been quartered, from eight in 19=
85 to two in 2022.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not sure if this chart is adjusted for inflation =E2=80=93 if n=
ot, adjusting for 2.78x inflation over the period would make it look a lot =
less severe =E2=80=93 but in either case, even the number of people in thes=
e newer, fancier jobs needed to produce newer, less survival-critical goods=
 and services is declining.=C2=A0
And while it=E2=80=99s relatively easy to increase rates, it=E2=80=99s hard=
 to see the trend towards fewer people being required to meet any type of n=
eed slowing down any time soon. In Power to the Person [ https://www.notbor=
ing.co/p/power-to-the-person ], I predicted that =E2=80=9CWithin two decade=
s, we will have multiple trillion-plus dollar publicly traded entities with=
 just one full-time employee, the founder.=E2=80=9D If you believe the AI a=
ccelerationists, or even the AI safety folks [ https://www.youtube.com/watc=
h?v=3DgA1sNLL6yg4 ], I may have been too conservative. We might be approach=
ing a world in which an entity with zero =E2=80=9Chumans=E2=80=9D can creat=
e untold value or destruction.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m nowhere near smart enough to set a timeline on AGI. Some people=
 think it=E2=80=99ll be here by 2025; others think it will be decades. And =
since we=E2=80=99re bad at predicting the impact of even technologies that =
we understand, I=E2=80=99m not going to try to predict the impact of one th=
at we don=E2=80=99t really. But zooming out and putting a fuzzy end date on=
 the graph, there=E2=80=99s a point in the future at which the productivity=
 per person looks like this:
So what do we do when we actually need very few people to work to make the =
economy go? The person who might have the biggest hand in bringing about th=
at future has an idea.=C2=A0
On Friday, OpenAI=E2=80=99s Sam Altman wrote a post titled Planning for AGI=
 and beyond [ https://openai.com/blog/planning-for-agi-and-beyond/ ] in whi=
ch he lays out the company=E2=80=99s plans to balance AI progress and safet=
y. Near the end of the piece, he includes a little aside on how the company=
 might help workers displaced by AGI. Its nonprofit can override for-profit=
 interests, and do things like =E2=80=9Csponsor the world=E2=80=99s most co=
mprehensive UBI experiment.=E2=80=9D
UBI is a way to spread the wealth when fewer people and companies produce a=
nd capture more economic value. Like, say, if one company develops an AGI t=
hat can do everything that people used to do, UBI would be a way to take a =
bunch of the money they make and give it to everyone so they can keep livin=
g and buying stuff.=C2=A0
UBI is ZIRP on steroids rolled up with perma-stimmies. Instead of saying, =
=E2=80=9CHere, you can borrow money for practically nothing but you=E2=80=
=99ll need to pay us back,=E2=80=9D UBI says, =E2=80=9CHere, take this mone=
y.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s how, for all intents and purposes, this popular ra=
tes chart goes from this:
To this=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
If you think that the creator economy or monkey jpegs or tech PM day in the=
 life TikToks were ZIRP Phenomena, wait until you see what people do with t=
heir time when they get paid just to be alive. UBI Phenomena will make ZIRP=
 Phenomena look quaint.=C2=A0
Now, as I will caveat many times here, while I studied econ in college, I a=
m not an economist. The economists among you are likely yelling all the rea=
son rates have declined for the past forty years at your computer screens. =
Rates were super high in 1980! Globalization! Aging population! Savings glu=
t! Marginal Revolution readers might even point out that Total Factor Produ=
ctivity growth has been anemic since 1973 [ https://marginalrevolution.com/=
marginalrevolution/2011/04/total-factor-productivity.html ]. Even that poin=
t, though, is debatable, since the blog post Tyler Cowen links to [ http://=
macromarketmusings.blogspot.com/2011/02/great-stagnation-and-total-factor.h=
tml ] in his post argues that TFP might be off because it=E2=80=99s harder =
to measure outputs from services and technology, which have made huge gains=
 in their share of the economy.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m just going to keep it stupid simple and look at how many Americ=
ans it takes to meet Americans=E2=80=99 basic needs for food and things, an=
d extrapolate from there, and assume that something similar is going to hap=
pen to knowledge work, too.=C2=A0
In The Enchanted Notebook [ https://www.notboring.co/p/the-enchanted-notebo=
ok ], I wrote about Ray Kurzweil=E2=80=99s superpower:
On the one side are experts, who understand the day-to-day difficulties of =
actually making Kurzweil=E2=80=99s predictions come true; on the other is K=
urzweil, who looks at the curves and trusts that they=E2=80=99ll continue.
It=E2=80=99s easy to get caught up in the short-term stuff and miss the big=
ger picture, so at the risk of looking very stupid, we=E2=80=99re going to =
Trust the Curves, before turning to some of my favorite sci-fi writers to s=
ee where those curves might be leading us.=C2=A0
Fewer People Are Keeping Us Alive
Over the past couple of centuries, the proportion of Americans working to m=
eet the population=E2=80=99s basic needs has declined dramatically thanks t=
o scientific and technological innovation, automation, and globalization. S=
o we invented new jobs, and financialized the economy, to meet brand new ne=
eds higher up Maslow=E2=80=99s Hierarchy and to keep people busy and filled=
 with meaning. Many of those jobs are now on the cusp of being automated aw=
ay too.=C2=A0
The most incredible stat I=E2=80=99ve come across on this front comes from =
Vaclav Smil=E2=80=99s How the World Really Works [ https://www.amazon.com/H=
ow-World-Really-Works-Science-ebook/dp/B09CDB69WT/?&&s=3Dbooks&sprefix=3Dho=
w+the+world+%2Cstripbooks%2C70&sr=3D1-1 ]: =E2=80=9Cthe share of the US pop=
ulation working as farmers declined from 83% in 1800 to 1% today.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
That is unbelievable. I want you to pause and take a second to think about =
it. That means that 223 years ago, 83 out of every 100 of us would have ess=
entially had to grow our own food to survive, and we no longer do, so we ca=
n do all sorts of other things. I just read Tim Urban=E2=80=99s book [ http=
s://www.amazon.com/Whats-Our-Problem-Self-Help-Societies-ebook/dp/B0BTJCTR5=
8/?&&sprefix=3Dtim+urb%2Caps%2C134&sr=3D8-1 ], so I=E2=80=99ll show you how=
 crazy that is using stick figures.=C2=A0
A lot has happened between then and now. We didn=E2=80=99t go to bed farmer=
s one day and wake up newsletter writers the next. So I pulled some data to=
 show what that chart looks like over time (Our World in Data ag data start=
s in 1840, so I used Smil=E2=80=99s 1800 number):=C2=A0
Share of workers in agriculture is not a perfect measure of the health of t=
he economy or progress. There are conflating factors, like the fact that at=
 some point on this graph we started importing more food. But I think it=E2=
=80=99s a really interesting one, because it shows the percentage of the po=
pulation focused on meeting people=E2=80=99s most basic need: food. Food is=
 energy, and without it, we die and nothing else matters.=C2=A0
All sorts of inputs go into this graph: mechanization, automation, biology,=
 chemistry, factory farming. The output is that it takes fewer people to fe=
ed more and more people. And the fewer people working on feeding us, the mo=
re people to work on satisfying other needs, for others or for themselves.=
=C2=A0
The Industrial Revolution was a major driver of the need for fewer farmers,=
 and a major recipient of former farmers. By 1910, 32% of non-farm employee=
s worked in manufacturing. By 1959, when FRED=E2=80=99s data starts, somewh=
ere between 8-9% of all Americans (working or not, everyone) were employed =
in manufacturing. Then around 1980, that percentage began to drop. Today, l=
ess than 4% of the population works in manufacturing.=C2=A0
Again, this data isn=E2=80=99t perfect. The US signed a bilateral trade agr=
eement with China in 1979, for example, so this chart is as much a result o=
f outsourcing as it is automation or efficiency. But the rough takeaway is =
that dramatically fewer Americans work to feed and make things for the grow=
ing population.=C2=A0
And if you zoom in on the period when rates start their four-decade downtre=
nd, right around 1980, the percentage of people making our things and growi=
ng our food each got cut in half over the four decades during which rates s=
teadily declined.=C2=A0
For the third time, this is messy data! Correlation-causation alarm bells a=
re blaring! Outsourcing and global trade play a big role! It=E2=80=99s not =
just productivity gains!=C2=A0
BUT if you stick with me here, you can see that more jobs doing things we n=
eed to survive are being automated (or outsourced) away, and rates are decl=
ining.=C2=A0
At the same time, the US employment rate is lower than it=E2=80=99s been si=
nce the 1950s.=C2=A0
Where are all the new jobs coming from? The biggest gainers, where both the=
 number of total jobs and the category=E2=80=99s percentage of total nonfar=
m jobs are higher in 2023 than 1980, are:
Education and Health Services: +17.995 million (mostly healthcare)
Professional and Business Services: +15.424 million
Leisure and Hospitality: +9.737 million=C2=A0
Financial Activities:=C2=A0 +4.158 million=C2=A0
Other Services (Repair, Laundry, Membership Orgs): +3.115 million
Trade, Transportation, and Utilities (+10.363 million) and Government (+6.1=
88 million) are both up, but have seen their share of the overall pie shrin=
k. You can play with the data here [ https://fred.stlouisfed.org/release/ta=
bles?rid=3D50&eid=3D4881&od=3D# ] if you want to dig in further.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
Other than healthcare, which is its own special clusterfuck, this is really=
 interesting to me because it looks like everything is moving up a layer or=
 two of abstraction and down a layer or two of necessity. Fewer people maki=
ng things, more people managing things being made, managing the money from =
those things being made, and cleaning and fixing the things that were made.=
 Fewer people growing food, more people serving other people food.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not surprising. Services =E2=80=93 including everything from=
 hospitality to professional and business services to financial activities =
=E2=80=93 have been steadily eating US GDP since as far back as Our World i=
n Data=E2=80=99s chart goes. Services as a percentage of GDP have doubled f=
rom ~40% in 1839 to ~80% today.=C2=A0
Over the past couple of centuries, and certainly over the past forty-odd ye=
ars, as fewer people have had to work hand-to-mouth or hand-to-machine, the=
 economy has had to support an increasing proportion of jobs that aren=E2=
=80=99t entirely necessary to our survival. And that=E2=80=99s great! The p=
oint of progress is to move more people up the hierarchy of needs. The poor=
est among us have things that Kings and Queens couldn=E2=80=99t have dreame=
d of even a century ago.=C2=A0
As automation marches on, even as we dream up newer and weirder jobs for ou=
rselves (I write an email newsletter!), the proportion of necessary jobs sh=
rinks. And now, it looks as if AI is coming for those less necessary knowle=
dge work jobs. It might even come after manual service jobs soon=E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0
What is everyone going to do for work when the robots can fulfill our basic=
 needs, and then some?
Luckily, this is a question that sci-fi writers have been wrestling with fo=
r a long time.=C2=A0
Vonnegut and Asimov Predict the Future
Is automation going to lead to a depressing, meaningless future of work or =
a beautiful world of aristocratic abundance for all? It depends if you beli=
eve Kurt Vonnegut or Isaac Asimov.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Kurt Vonnegut came out swinging. In his 1952 debut novel, Player Piano, he =
described a near-future America in which automation has created widespread =
unemployment, unrest, and ennui.=C2=A0
The engineering-inclined held jobs maintaining the machines and directing t=
heir output. Everyone else was left with two choices: join the Army, or wor=
k for the Reconstruction and Reclamation Corps.=C2=A0
What did members of the Reconstruction and Reclamation Corps do? Glad you a=
sked, because that=E2=80=99s the image that=E2=80=99s been glued to my othe=
rwise spotty memory ever since I read the book. They dug holes in the road,=
 and then they filled them back in.=C2=A0
Vonnegut was clearly inspired by two experiences, one personal and one nati=
onal.=C2=A0
After serving in World War II, and before quitting to try his hand at writi=
ng, Vonnegut spent three years at General Electric, where he worked alongsi=
de engineers who wanted to automate everything. According to the person who=
 interviewed him for Playboy [ https://web.archive.org/web/20090210155908/h=
ttp://www.playboy.com/magazine/interview_archive/kurt-vonnegut/kurt-vonnegu=
t-3.html ] in 1973 [ https://web.archive.org/web/20090210155908/http://www.=
playboy.com/magazine/interview_archive/kurt-vonnegut/kurt-vonnegut-3.html ]=
, =E2=80=9CIt seemed to him that scientists in those days wanted to mechani=
ze everything and take care of everybody.=E2=80=9D
Before that, during his teenage years in the 1930s, Vonnegut saw Franklin D=
=2E Roosevelt=E2=80=99s Works Progress Ad=
ministration use federal funds to em=
ploy millions of unemployed Americans in public works projects to help over=
come a temporary Great Depression.=C2=A0
Player Piano asked, =E2=80=9CWhat if the GE engineers get their way?=E2=80=
=9D and answered with a nihilistic twist on the WPA. As Vonnegut told Playb=
oy:
Player Piano was my response to the implications of having everything run b=
y little boxes. The idea of doing that, you know, made sense, perfect sense=
=2E To have a little clicking box make al=
l the decisions wasn't a vicious thi=
ng to do. But it was too bad for the human beings who got their dignity fro=
m their jobs.
If we reach the point, in a decade or a century, when most people don=E2=80=
=99t need to work to make a living for society to function, what will we do=
 with all of our time? Whence will we get dignity?
Writing a decade after Vonnegut, Isaac Asimov saw a similar fate for human =
employment =E2=80=93 no longer necessary, really =E2=80=93 but imagined a v=
ery different, more optimistic outcome. In Whatever You Wish [ http://hermi=
ene.net/essays-trans/whatever_you_wish.html ], which is so excellent that I=
=E2=80=99m just going to include the whole thing here, he wrote, =E2=80=9CI=
 can=E2=80=99t help but think, however, that the advance of computerization=
 and automation is going to wipe out the subwork of humanity =E2=80=93 the =
dull pushing and shoving and punching and clicking and filing and all the o=
ther simple and repetitive motions, both physical and mental, that can be d=
one perfectly easily =E2=80=93 and better =E2=80=93 by machines no more com=
plicated than those we can already build.=E2=80=9D
While acknowledging that the thought of being automated out of a job could =
be =E2=80=9Cfrightening,=E2=80=9D Asimov envisioned a world in which machin=
es allow humans to be more human. Instead of doing what we have to do to su=
rvive, humans might spend their time like aristocrats of old, becoming =E2=
=80=9Ceducated in literature, the arts, and philosophy.=E2=80=9D Of course,=
 people could choose impactful work in fields like =E2=80=9Ccomputer techno=
logy or fusion engineering or lunar mining or any of the professions that w=
ould seem vital to the proper functioning of the world,=E2=80=9D but that w=
ould be entirely up to them. =E2=80=9CEvery field will be an elective, and =
the only guide will be =E2=80=98whatever you wish.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As we hurtle towards that automated future, the question is: whose vision i=
s more right, Vonnegut or Asimov?=C2=A0
The general dialogue around automation would suggest that Vonnegut=E2=80=99=
s is the more popularly held. I=E2=80=99ve written about the fear that robo=
ts will steal factory jobs [ https://www.notboring.co/p/formic-automating-a=
bundance ], despite evidence to the contrary. Each recent advance in AI=E2=
=80=99s capabilities have been met with concerns about the economic prospec=
ts for artists, writers, MBAs, lawyers, and even doctors. If Vonnegut=E2=80=
=99s right, we=E2=80=99ll end up unemployed, undignified, unsatisfied, unfu=
lfilled. Maybe we=E2=80=99ll dig some holes, and fill them back in.
But me, I think that Asimov was more prescient. His vision is kind of alrea=
dy happening now. We=E2=80=99re just wrapping =E2=80=9Cwhatever we wish=E2=
=80=9D in games masquerading as jobs.=C2=A0
The Present and Far Future of Work
We=E2=80=99re still some years away from computers and robots wiping out th=
e subwork of humanity, so the jury is still out, but I think if Asimov miss=
ed something, it=E2=80=99s that humans are competitive animals who derive m=
eaning from work. Maybe this, too, will change with time, but until thousan=
ds of years of evolution=E2=80=99s hard wiring are re-wired, I assume we=E2=
=80=99ll want to keep striving towards something.=C2=A0
My guess is that work and games are going to continue to blend.
My most popular essay ever, The Great Online Game [ https://www.notboring.c=
o/p/the-great-online-game ], touched on this idea a bit. The internet is li=
ke a big, global game with real-world consequences. But what I=E2=80=99m ta=
lking about here is a little different.=C2=A0
A couple weeks ago, I was listening to Episode 4 of the excellent  [ https:=
//open.spotify.com/episode/10GsRWexiOT9NhK0CsAKEx?si=3D7177d55cee0e4937 ]Ga=
mecraft  [ https://open.spotify.com/episode/10GsRWexiOT9NhK0CsAKEx?si=3D717=
7d55cee0e4937 ]podcast [ https://open.spotify.com/episode/10GsRWexiOT9NhK0C=
sAKEx?si=3D7177d55cee0e4937 ] from Benchmark=E2=80=99s Mitch Lasky [ https:=
//twitter.com/mitchlasky ] and Blake Robbins [ https://twitter.com/blakeir =
] when I found a set of criteria that fit even better. The episode was titl=
ed =E2=80=9CThe Forever Games,=E2=80=9D and near the very beginning, Lasky =
laid out the five key attributes of Forever Games, =E2=80=9Cgames designed =
to last for a really long time.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Balance: all players have a fair shot at winning the game.=C2=A0
Community: ability to form relationships with other people who play the gam=
e.
Eventfulness: events, like new seasons, drive people back to the game.=C2=
=A0
Competition: find other players who challenge you and compete to win.
Player Investment: invest time and/or money in building up skills and asset=
s.
Not every Forever Game needs to be 100% on every category, but they need to=
 have at least a little of each, and ideally a lot of some.=C2=A0
That framework fits a lot of the jobs that have become more popular since t=
he 1800s, and especially over the past forty years. Hedge funds are an obvi=
ous example, but many less obvious ones fit, too. Academia, product managem=
ent, certainly newsletter writing. Think about your job: would you say it=
=E2=80=99s more =E2=80=9Clife or death=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cgame-like=E2=80=
=9D? When I asked that question on Twitter, 81% of respondents went with ga=
me-like:
At the same time, games are becoming more like work. In The New Gold Rush [=
 https://open.spotify.com/episode/43eOX95d4XBSDPAhmETy0n?si=3D5252cd4c778d4=
c9d ], Lasky and Robbins described economic play in games like EVE Online, =
in which players formed mini-economies, complete with division of labor and=
 assigned jobs. Even in virtual worlds, with no real stakes, people find wa=
ys to work together to create things they can=E2=80=99t on their own.=C2=A0
Not everyone will play games, directly or wrapped-as-work. As Asimov predic=
ted, there will always be people who want to dedicate their lives to solvin=
g the hardest challenges facing humanity =E2=80=93 like nuclear fusion, lun=
ar mining, and the whole Good Quests list [ https://www.piratewires.com/p/c=
hoose-good-quests ]. I want to fund them and help tell their stories, and I=
 hope that a consequence of persistently low rates and software automation,=
 if that comes to pass, is that resources can flow to the companies that ne=
ed a lot of capital to achieve really hard and important things.=C2=A0
But many others are already engaged in jobs that require an applied version=
 of Asimov=E2=80=99s broad liberal arts program. Learn broadly, and apply t=
he knowledge to games wrapped up as work.
I=E2=80=99ll pick on myself here. I get to spend my days reading, having co=
nversations with really smart people, making =E2=80=9Cart,=E2=80=9D and wri=
ting. My days sound a lot like what Asimov predicted they would. But I need=
 to make a living and feel like I=E2=80=99m making some sort of difference,=
 so I send this newsletter to 188k people and try to grow it and find spons=
ors and compete to invest in companies that have a shot at making life bett=
er for humans and try to help them win. It=E2=80=99s a modern aristocratic =
life, wrapped in a work game.=C2=A0
Not Boring =E2=80=93 the newsletter and the Fund =E2=80=93 could be conside=
red a ZIRP Phenomenon. Some random guy sits in his house writing and invest=
ing instead of building something with his bare hands. But if I had to bet,=
 I=E2=80=99d guess that the jobs of the future look more like Not Boring, a=
nd even weirder. We=E2=80=99ll continue to push out the Pareto Funtier [ ht=
tps://www.notboring.co/p/the-pareto-funtier ], with =E2=80=9Cfun=E2=80=9D d=
efined for each person as =E2=80=9Cwhatever you wish.=E2=80=9D
If Altman, Vonnegut, Asimov, and Banks are right and we land in a spot wher=
e people don=E2=80=99t need to work, they=E2=80=99ll still need to find mea=
ning. They=E2=80=99ll still want to compete, and outperform their neighbors=
=2E Most billionaires continue working long after they have to.=C2=A0
That world, if it comes to pass, will make ZIRP Phenomena look like the goo=
d ol=E2=80=99 days, when people rolled up their sleeves and made an honest =
living. When no one has to work to survive, the things we make up to keep o=
urselves busy will look increasingly silly. But we=E2=80=99ll take them rea=
lly fucking seriously. The love of the game will create meaning, community,=
 and yes, consumption. And when those games get old, we=E2=80=99ll create n=
ewer, wilder ones.=C2=A0
Of course, I hope that people will take advantage of the need to work less =
to actually work less, to spend more quality time with their family and fri=
ends, to explore the world and connect with a higher purpose. As we pointed=
 out in last week=E2=80=99s Weekly Dose, one consequence of increased produ=
ctivity has been that most people work less: college, retirement, and weeke=
nds are all relatively recent phenomena. This trend, too, will likely conti=
nue. We=E2=80=99ll get to play games for work and work less, if we wish.=C2=
=A0
Long before AGI, there are nearer-term implications that will impact many o=
f us. I=E2=80=99ve written about a couple of them this year, in Differentia=
tion [ https://www.notboring.co/p/differentiation ] and Love in the Time of=
 Replika [ https://www.notboring.co/p/love-in-the-time-of-replika ]. Over t=
he next few weeks, I have a few more planned out. I suspect that a lot of w=
hat I write in this newsletter in the coming months and years will be about=
 the businesses bringing about this weird, abundant future and what will be=
 different when they do.=C2=A0
If this really is one of those =E2=80=9Ceverything is changing=E2=80=9D mom=
ents, it=E2=80=99s going to keep me busy and employed=E2=80=A6 until it tak=
es my job, too.
Thanks to Dan [ https://twitter.com/damccormick13 ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your podcast feeds t=
his week and your inbox on Friday for that Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

